<div id="review_1711501408" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1711501408" />
    <a title="Atiqah Ghazali" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58139353-atiqah-ghazali"><img alt="Atiqah Ghazali" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1474237188p2/58139353.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1711501408?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Atiqah Ghazali" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Atiqah Ghazali" href="/user/show/58139353-atiqah-ghazali">Atiqah Ghazali</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1711501408" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer115084750061609722">I picked up this book after I found out that this piece is recommended by Khaled Hosseini. In addition to that, I was obsessively fanatic with the culture and pre/post-war of Afghanistan. <br/><br/>As this book was originally written in French language by the author, the publisher hired a translator that is fond of using a higher prose of English language. When there is one word that I&apos;m unsure of the meaning, it put me off quite quickly. Luckily, the magnet of Afghan made me reluctant to give it up.<br/><br/>The t</span>
  <span id="freeText115084750061609722" style="display:none">I picked up this book after I found out that this piece is recommended by Khaled Hosseini. In addition to that, I was obsessively fanatic with the culture and pre/post-war of Afghanistan. <br /><br />As this book was originally written in French language by the author, the publisher hired a translator that is fond of using a higher prose of English language. When there is one word that I'm unsure of the meaning, it put me off quite quickly. Luckily, the magnet of Afghan made me reluctant to give it up.<br /><br />The translator used many adjectives in his description of the situation. Though the words are benignly beautiful, it somehow only scratches the epidermis of the emotion. It didn't evoke the thunderstorms or the tsunamis of it although I longed for it to do so.<br /><br />Nevertheless, the feminist in me screamed when I read about how the men suggested Mussarat to be divorced or when Zunaira was forced to wear the burqa. My liberal state couldn't process this thought without trying to yell to the men characters. <br /><br />I recommend this book. It still engrossed me, though it hits below my expectation. I finished the whole book in less than 4 hours in one sitting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="115084750061609722" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


